default&#xa0;defaultThe government’s strategy
defaultImmunisation and anti-microbial agents, particularly antibiotics, have made an enormous contribution to control of infectious disease and reduction of early death in the UK and throughout the world.  However, as emphasised in the Chief Medical Officer’s Annual report, AMR is now a major problem.  Important contributory factors include inappropriate prescribing of antibiotics and their routine use in animal husbandry as growth promoters.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe government’s strategy on AMR focuses on: 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhile these are important, in our view the focus is too narrow.  This is essentially a convergent, ‘more of the same’ approach.  Unless there is a turnaround in the long-term downward trend in antibiotic discovery, this strategy will slow the spread of AMR, but not reverse it.   
default&#xa0;
defaultThe evidence in the CMO’s report is largely hospital based with little reference to primary care and no mention of self-care.  Yet most inappropriate antibiotic prescribing occurs in primary care for self-limiting viral upper respiratory tract infections, despite numerous public health campaigns advising symptomatic measures such as rest, 
defaultparacetamol
default and increased fluid intake rather than antibiotics for colds, coughs and sore throats. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe advocate a more divergent approach incorporating, in addition to the measures proposed in the CMO’s Annual Report, research into other treatment options.  In particular, we believe that the potential of integrating traditional and 
defaulttraditioanl
default and complementary medicine methods, and the promotion of safe and appropriate self-care should be investigated.  
default&#xa0;
defaultPrimary care research projects on herbal medicine in infectious disease
defaultA number of research projects with implications for AMR in, particularly around herbal treatment, are in progress at the National School for Primary Care Research.  These include:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultProjects submitted for funding, or in advanced development include:
default&#xa0;
defaultThe clinical input in all these studies has involved collaboration between primary care departments within the NIHR National School for Primary Care Research.    The UCL School of Pharmacy has provided 
defaultphytopharmacy
default input.  These projects reflect a sustained strategy designed to provide alternatives to antibiotics in primary care, led by departments of research excellence and high quality researchers including Prof Paul Little (Southampton University), 
defaultProf Chris Butler (Cardiff and Oxford University) and Prof Simon Gibbons (UCL School of Pharmacy)
default&#xa0;
defaultPromising herbal medicines
defaultCurrent evidence and systematic reviews suggest that herbs may have specific effects on acute infections and may also act synergistically with conventional medicines including antibiotics to diminish the risk of AMR. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the absence of effective antiviral orthodox therapy for self-limiting non-threatening viral infections, which are sometimes inappropriately treated with antibiotics or maybe complicated by bacterial 
defaultsuperinfection
default, a number of herbal extracts have potential.  These include: 
defaultAndrographis
default 
defaultpaniculata
default, 
defaultPelargonium 
defaultsidoides
default (a species of geranium), 
defaultEchinacea species
default, 
defaultgarlic
default, and 
defaultSambucus
default 
defaultnigra
default (elderberry), all of these are currently available in the UK as registered herbal medicines, and have shown promise in clinical trials for treatment or prevention of the common cold, acute bronchitis and sinusitis, and influenza. [2-7]
defaultThe evidence suggests that they may act directly as antiviral agents and also stimulate boost immune system anti-viral activity. Replication of these results in independent, large, high quality clinical trials (such as is currently planned for 
defaultPelargonium
default), combined with education of healthcare practitioners, community pharmacists, and the public, have the potential to enhance self-care, reduce GP attendances and antibiotic prescriptions, and allow patients to receive effective treatment for self-limiting viral illnesses.
defaultThe potential of herbs and plant extracts to potentiate antibiotics is a promising area for development, this includes some of the most dangerous antimicrobial resistant organisms.  At present most such work is preliminary and laboratory-based. But a recent review found evidence that 34 herbs may have such effects. 
default&#xa0;
