default&#xa0;defaultHomeopathy
defaultHomeopathy is controversial but is associated with reduced use of antibiotics in upper respiratory tract infections, an important source of inappropriate antibiotic prescribing in primary care.  This may be a result of the enhanced self-care that frequently occurs when patients seek and self-manage with CAM or it may be a specific effect. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA Health Technology Assessment commissioned by the Swiss Federal government found 29 clinical trials of homeopathy for upper respiratory tract infection or allergies found 29 clinical studies of which 24 were positive for homeopathy.   When the 16 randomised placebo-controlled, trials only were analysed 8/16 were found to be statistically significantly positive, 4/16
default 
defaultshowed a positive trend.
default 
defaultOf trials comparing homeopathy with conventional treatment, 6/7 trials showed at least equivalence: 1/7 superior to conventional treatment, 5/7 equivalent to conventional treatment, one showed homeopathy to be inferior to conventional treatment (homeopathy v penicillin for streptococcal 
defaultpharyngitis
default or tonsillitis).   The conclusion for homeopathy is ‘
defaultprobable effectiveness’. [12]
default&#xa0;
defaultA study published since this Health Technology Assessment, supported by the Indian Ministry of Health involved collaboration between conventional ENT specialists and homeopathic doctors in a randomised controlled trial of homeopathy v conventional treatment in acute 
defaultotitis
default media.  The outcomes at 3 weeks were not significantly different, but the numbers of antibiotic prescriptions in the 
defaulthomeopathically
default-treated group were much lower. [13-14]
default&#xa0;
defaultOther evidence relevant to AMR includes preliminary clinical trial data suggesting that homeopathy may improve outcomes of critically-ill patients in intensive care units, and that it may be an effective treatment for E coli diarrhoea in newborn piglets. [15-16]
default&#xa0;
defaultDeveloping self care 
defaultSelf-care is strongly associated with use of traditional and complementary medicine. 
defaultThere is huge potential to develop self-care with 
defaulttraditional and complementary medicine 
defaultto manage the symptoms of acute infections and thus avoid patients requesting antibiotics.  
default&#xa0;
defaultTraining community pharmacists in evidence based understanding of 
defaulttraditional and complementary 
defaultbased approaches to self-care in acute self-limiting infections would increase their opportunist repertoire and allow patients who prefer such interventions more treatment options.  NHS Direct should provide appropriate guidance to the public.  In another domain (cancer), the website of Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Centre in New York City is an exemplar of public information on integrative medicine. [17]
default&#xa0;
defaultConclusions
defaultTraditional and complementary medicine methods have great potential for avoiding or averting the use of antibiotics, potentiating their effectiveness, and as novel antimicrobial agents.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition, traditional and complementary medicine is strongly associated with self-care.  With appropriate promotion of their safe use and training of health care professionals, this can make a significant contribution to the reduction of inappropriate use of antimicrobial agents.
default&#xa0;
defaultConsidering its potential traditional and complementary medicine for AMR is greatly under researched.  Its potential should be taken into account in developing national AMR policy.
